":"1515","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Farnham, Surrey, England":"Farnham, Surrey, England","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Dean Hill, Cheshire, England":"Dean Hill, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jervas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Athanasios, Christos, Demetre, Dionisios, Efstratios, Ioannis, Markos, Photios, Spiro, Tasos, Vasilios.","Greek: variant of   Zervos  .","Dutch and North German: from a vernacular form of the medieval personal name   Servatius  , a Christian saint's name."],"variants":[{"name":"Zirbel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Fritz.","German: from a pet form of a variant of the personal name   Zervas  ."]},{"name":"Zervos","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Thanos, Christos, Constantine, Constantinos, Diamantis, Spero, Stratis, Theophilos.","Greek: from the vocabulary word <i>zervos</i>, a nickname meaning ‘left-handed’, ultimately from Arabic <i>zāwiya</i> ‘corner, angle’."]},{"name":"Zerbel","meanings":["German: from a pet form of a variant of the personal name   Zervas   2."]},{"name":"Zirbes","meanings":["German: variant of   Zervas  ."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"Gervas","type":"LAST","meanings":["From the Old German ger~wisa, a war leader; or ger-wis, very wise or prudent."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Martimer","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a Norman baronial name borne by the lords of <i>Mortemer</i> in Normandy. The place name meant ‘dead sea’ in Old French, and probably referred to a stagnant marsh. It was not used as a given name until the 19th century. Among Jews it has been adopted as an Anglicized form of   Moses   and in Ireland as an Anglicized form of Muiriartach ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Martimer Jervas or Gervas was born in 1480, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, his father, John Bishop, was 15 and his mother, Lady Margaret Milbourne, was 13. He had at l